he often-problematic reliance upon ‘official’ sources when forming historical narratives, it demonstrates the contested value awarded to public inquiries – contrastingly viewed by black Britons as either a method for increased political participation or simply a governmental diversionary tactic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBlacksxPolitical activityzGreat Britainy20th century. 0aPolitical violencezGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aRacismzGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aRiotszGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aBlack British.  aThatcher.  aactivism.  apolicing.  apolitical participation.  aprotest.  apublic inquiries.  arace.  aracism.  ariots.1 aPeplow, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2019 eBook-Packagez978311128249740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152612529340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526125293423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526125293/original  a978-3-11-128249-7  Manchester University Press 2019 eBook-Packageb2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles